Cell B10 | value='Biotope classification for 1988. Each sediment profile image was first assigned to a sediment grain size category, then biota were described from the biotic surface and subsurface features. These elements were summarized into a short phrase using the sediment grain size descriptor and dominant biota. Non-dominant but conspicuous biota were included in the descriptions when present. More detailed biota and sediment descriptions and the designated biotope for each SPI image replicate are presented in Shumchenia and King (2019). [AM: Ampelisca beds occasionally with other small tube-building and shallowburrowing fauna on substrates ranging from organic-rich muds to sand. Beggiatoa spp. or Mulinia lateralis may be present; SA: Hard sands with epibenthic sponges, rafting or attached macroalgae, and/or mobile gastropods; SH.SA: Very coarse sands with shell hash. Rafting macroalgae or Crepidula beds may be present; SH.SI: Crepidula bed on mud. Mobile crustaceans, gastropods, or Beggiatoa spp. may be presen; UN.SF: Organic-rich mud with tolerant species such as Beggiatoa spp., tube-building polychaetes, and shallow burrowing fauna; UN.SH: Burrowing fauna on mud with shell hash. Tube-building polychaetes or deep burrowing fauna may be present; UN.SI: Burrowing fauna on mud. Tubebuilding polychaetes, larger tubebuilders such as Chaetopterus, or deep burrowing fauna may be present; UN.SS: Burrowing and tube-building fauna on sandy mud; UN.ST: Small tube-building fauna on mud or organic-rich mud. Larger tube builders, such as Chaetopterus, and shallow or deep-burrowing fauna may be present.; NA: Station not sampled and/or no images obtained from station and/or images missing from the archive, preventing reanalysis; indet: Images were collected but not interpretable for biotope classification.)' | fill=00000000 | rows=[9] | cols=[1] | col_header=False | row_header=False | metadata=False
